      "source": [
        "### 5. Sets\n",
        "\n",
        "**Concept:** Sets are unordered, mutable collections of *unique* items. They are primarily used for membership testing and eliminating duplicate entries. They are defined using curly braces `{}` (or `set()` for an empty set).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Used In Program:**\n",
        "```python\n",
        "my_set = {\"cat\", \"dog\", \"bird\", \"cat\"}\n",
        "my_set.add(\"fish\")\n",
        "another_set = {\"dog\", \"elephant\", \"mouse\"}\n",
        "print(my_set.union(another_set))\n",
        "print(my_set.intersection(another_set))\n",
        "for animal in my_set:\n",
        "    # ...\n",
        "```\n",
        "- **Creation:** `my_set = {...}`. Duplicates provided during creation are automatically removed.\n",
        "- **Uniqueness:** Sets only store one copy of each distinct element.\n",
        "- **Operations:** Support mathematical set operations like union, intersection, difference, and symmetric difference.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Expected Output:** Displays the set (with duplicates removed), after adding an item, and the results of union and intersection operations. Iterates through and prints each unique element.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Alternative Methods/Notes:**\n",
        "- **Empty Set:** To create an empty set, use `set()` (not `{}` which creates an empty dictionary).\n",
        "- **Set Comprehension:** `my_set = {x for x in my_list if x > 5}`."
      ]
    },
