      "source": [
        "### 9. Exception Handling\n",
        "\n",
        "**Concept:** Exception handling allows you to gracefully manage errors (exceptions) that occur during program execution, preventing the program from crashing. It uses `try`, `except`, `else`, and `finally` blocks.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Used In Program:**\n",
        "```python\n",
        "try:\n",
        "    result = 10 / 0\n",
        "except ZeroDivisionError:\n",
        "    print(\"  Error: Cannot divide by zero!\")\n",
        "finally:\n",
        "    print(\"  Division attempt finished.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "try:\n",
        "    with open(\"non_existent_file.txt\", 'r') as f:\n",
        "        # ...\n",
        "except FileNotFoundError:\n",
        "    print(f\"  Error: File 'non_existent_file.txt' not found.\")\n",
        "```\n",
        "- **`try` block:** Contains the code that might raise an exception.\n",
        "- **`except` block:** Catches specific exceptions. If an exception listed here occurs in the `try` block, this code runs.\n",
        "- **`finally` block:** Always executes, regardless of whether an exception occurred or not. Useful for cleanup operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Expected Output:** Prints error messages for division by zero and file not found, along with the `finally` block messages.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Alternative Methods/Notes:**\n",
        "- **`else` block:** Executes if the `try` block completes without raising an exception.\n",
        "- **Multiple `except` blocks:** Can catch different types of exceptions (`except ZeroDivisionError`, `except TypeError`).\n",
        "- **Catching all exceptions:** `except Exception as e:` catches any exception and stores it in variable `e`."
      ]
    },
