        "### 11. Classes and Objects\n",
        "\n",
        "**Concept:** Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) allows you to model real-world entities using classes and objects. A **class** is a blueprint for creating objects, defining attributes (data) and methods (functions) that the objects will have. An **object** is an instance of a class.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Used In Program:**\n",
        "```python\n",
        "class Dog:\n",
        "    def __init__(self, name, breed):\n",
        "        self.name = name\n",
        "        self.breed = breed\n",
        "\n",
        "    def bark(self):\n",
        "        return f\"{self.name} says Woof!\"\n",
        "\n",
        "my_dog = Dog(\"Buddy\", \"Golden Retriever\")\n",
        "print(my_dog.name)\n",
        "print(my_dog.bark())\n",
        "```\n",
        "- **`class Dog:`:** Defines a class named `Dog`.\n",
        "- **`__init__(self, ...)`:** The constructor method. It's called automatically when a new object is created. `self` refers to the instance of the class.\n",
        "- **`self.name`, `self.breed`:** Instance variables (attributes) specific to each object.\n",
        "- **`bark(self)`:** An instance method (function belonging to the class) that operates on the object's data.\n",
        "- **`my_dog = Dog(...)`:** Creates an object (an instance) of the `Dog` class.\n",
        "- **`my_dog.name`, `my_dog.bark()`:** Accessing an object's attribute and calling its method.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Expected Output:** Prints the dog's name and the result of its `bark()` method.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Alternative Methods/Notes:**\n",
        "- **Inheritance:** Classes can inherit attributes and methods from other classes (`class Poodle(Dog):`).\n",
        "- **Polymorphism:** Objects of different classes can be treated uniformly.\n",
        "- **Encapsulation:** Bundling data (attributes) and methods that operate on the data within a single unit (class)."
